  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002_19",
    "text": "Remark. This problem amounts to refuting a potential generalization of the Mean Value Theorem to bivariate functions. Many counterexamples are possible. Kent Merryfield suggests y sin(2x), for which all four of the boundary integrals vanish; here the partial derivatives are 2mycos (2x) and sin(2x). Catalin Zara suggests 21/3,2/3. Qingchun Ren suggests xy (1 - y).",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5545112806077694,
      0.23401162836024944,
      0.9210526389119592,
      0.337301587695409
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002",
    "order": 8
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002_4",
    "text": "for some nonnegative integers e1, e2,..., all but finitely many of which are 0.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
