  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002_9",
    "text": "Since s1 ≤ 52<.., k(G) + 1 is always divisible by 2\"'. In particular, k(G) = 2009 forces s1 ≤ 1.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781954002757723,
      0.45203488417420284,
      0.4906015005112703,
      0.47966269824990243
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002_10",
    "text": "However, the only cases where s1 ≤ 1 are where all of the ej are 0, in which case k(G) = 0, or where ei = 1 for some i and ej = 0 for j # i, in which case k(G) = (i 1)2' + 1. The right side is a strictly increasing function of i which equals 1793 for i = 8 and 4097 for i = 9, so it can never equal 2009. This proves the claim.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781955060871733,
      0.48685515893262554,
      0.49060151109241035,
      0.5712209302583944
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2009_Solutions_2009s_page_002_21",
    "text": "Remark. Noam Elkies points out that the representations are unique up to rearranging and canceling common factors.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5581589428735487,
      0.5735412442109866,
      0.9192735623526485,
